From: brand@addvax.llnl.gov (Hal R. Brand, LLnL, 510-422-6312)
Subject: Probable SLS 1.03 Kernel BUG
Date: 11 Sep 1993 20:30 PST

Bill Javurek (javurek@garnet.msen.com) reported difficulties with umount-ing
floppies; getting a device busy message. I too have seen this problem,
only my problem is worse than Bill reported.

Problem: Files systems won't "umount" following certain operations.
Kernel: Stock SLS 1.03 and rebuilt 1.03 kernel
File systems exhibiting problem: ext2 (on IDE) and minix (on floppy);
        others not tested.
Symptoms: Following certain operations it is impossible to "umount" the
        file system.
Impact: Even using the bootutils-0.1 and careful shutdowns, file system
        corruption has occasionally occured.
To Reproduce:
        (boot and login as root, mount an (expendable) FS)
        # /etc/umount <FS>              <== verify it umounts!
        # /etc/mount -t <type> <dev> <mount point>
        #cd <mount point>
        # emacs test.test
        <create some text and write out the text; exit emacs>
        # cd /
        # /etc/umount <mount point OR dev>   <== should get device busy!
        # logout                             <== rest is optional
        <login as root>
        # /etc/umount <mount point OR dev>   <== no help!
Fix: Get the original (i.e. straight from Linus) 0.99pl12 distribution,
        patch it with Linus's patch, and rebuild the kernel. Adding
        the sound driver is safe.
Other Info: I rebuilt the SLS 1.03 kernel turning off most all the patches
        put into the SLS 1.03 kernel except the sound driver and file
        quotas and still had the problem. I tried to turn off the quotas
        but the "ld" failed with a missing symbol so I had to reconfigure
        and rebuild! The umount problem remained. I can ante-up my
        kernel "config" file if needed, but the stock SLS 1.03 kernel also
        exhibits the problem.

I urge others out there verify this.

                                        Hal R. Brand
                                        LLNL
                                        brand@addvax.llnl.gov

------------------------------

Date: Fri, 10 Sep 93 12:00:00 +0200
From: Frank_Altenburg@privi.fido.de (Frank Altenburg)
Subject: Re^2: coprocessor makes LOTS of differen

 YO!

RP> >> 386-40 with Cyrix:       9 hours 23 minutes
RP> >> 486-33           :       11 hourand 10 minutes
RP> On a true 486DX-33, the built in coprocessor is FOUR TIMES as fast as a
386/387 combo running at the same speed.

RP> only wish for a coprocessor like that... especially since the MINIMUM time
RP> for a 387 SIN operation running at 33 MHz is 122 clocks, with the *AVERAGE*
RP> somewhere around 400 clocks.

OK, what you evaluate here may be correct in terms of math, but you have to
consider secondary effects. Obviously, the POV timing yield an AVERAGE VALUE
of computation time, so your above 122 clocks result can't really be derived
from the overall benchmarking result, I'd guess.

Rather, I'd like to introduce some benchm. results queried from the magazine
c't 4/90 p. 162 f. (published in German) which states the following relative
speeds  (with intel 80387, 25 MHz, no cache as 100%) :

Cyrix Fasmath 25 MHz                146 %       284 %      Mandelbrot (ovrAll)
Intel 486     25 MHz                130 %       443 %      real
(25 was a lot at the time ;) )      152 %       197 %      trigon & logarithm
                                    112 %       448 %      Matrix
let me just say that appearantly the measurement conditions are seemingly ok.

So, according to this, you say correctly that performance over 387 is 4 times,
except at special arithmetic (triLog), where it is only 20 % ,roughly.

Now, caching comes into play: Since Cyrix is an I/O device, there should be
now queue flushing when FLOAT ops are encountered.

That is to say that external caching improves float performance linearily.
Since 20% less performance already take into account the 8K onchip RAM of 486,
I do not find it hard to imagine that a cached 386/Cyrix FasMath can overtake
a 486 at particular operations, given the current design problems with
486 Boards (writeBack and such).
Yet, in general, it is hardly feasible to get onchip-integration-comm-speed
(like internal 486/487) with on-PCB integration (like Cyrix 486S + CoPro).
Nonetheless, I believe that a Cyrix machine really is nice silicon to put
in a socket...

               //////////////////////////////
               /      Greetinx, Frank       /
               //////////////////////////////



